Validation Log Feature of PICO
------------------------------

This feature is meant mainly for debugging of PICO internals.  The
idea is to provide a greater degree of confidence in PICO's output
than simply verifying that it computed the correct objective value.
In many branch-and-bound applications, the correct objective value is
identified quite early in the run, and subsequent errors, particularly
failure to explore parts of the tree that must be examined, could
easily go undetected.

The validation log feature basically allows PICO to dump a basic description
of the search tree as it runs.  Subsequently, you can use a log
analyzer program to verify that the search tree is believable.


The Information Produced by PICO
--------------------------------

To activate the validation log feature while running PICO, set the 
"validateLog" parameter to a non-zero value.  This parameter is a
member of the "branching" class.

If "validateLog" is non-zero, PICO produces log files of the form
valXXXXX.log in the current working directory, where XXXXX corresponds
to the processor rank.  If you are running a serial application, or a
parallel application with only one processor, only the file
val00000.log will be produced.  If, for example, you were running a
parallel application on 3 processors, files val00000.log, val00001.log,
and val00002,log would be produced.

Each file contains information on every subproblem creation,
unpacking, bounding, separation, and destruction operation performed
on the corresponding processor.  val00000.log will also contain
information on the final solution value and the criteria for fathoming
subproblems.

A minor note: log files produced by processors 1 and above may have
unexpected group id's and protection masks, depending on how MPI runs
parallel jobs.  Under MPICH on Solaris, for instance, processor ranks
1 and higher are created via the "rsh" command, and will have the
user's default group id and protections, even though the group id and
umask may have been set differently when the "mpirun" command was
issued.

Note also that validation logs corresponding to processor ranks higher
than those used in the present run are not automatically deleted.
For example, a run on 3 processors followed by a run on 2 processors
could result in a situation where val00000.log and val00001.log
correspond to the second 2-processor run, but val00002.log corresponds
to the 3-processor run.  This could cause a torrent of errors when the
logs are analyzed, so it is wise to delete all prior log files before
generating new ones.

Note also that the "destroy" events in the log files are generated by
the "recycle()" method for class branchSub (and classes derived from
it).  When destroying subproblems, this method must be used, as
opposed to the bare "delete" operator.  If this method is overridden,
these events could disappear, causing problems for the analyzer.  When
we get to the point that we're overriding the new and delete operators
for subproblems, we may have to be a little careful here.  We'd like
log file production to continue to work in a reasonably transparent
way.


Analyzing the Log Files
-----------------------

The log file analyzer program is called "logAnalyze", and currently
lives in the src/examples directory.

When you invoke it, you should give the names of all the log files
produced by the run you want to validate.  So a typical invocation
would be

	logAnalyze val[0-9]*.log

There must be at least one argument.  

The analyzer checks a wide variety of things: is every non-fathomable
problem bounded and separated?  Are all its children produced?  Do the
bounds trend in the correct direction as one moves down the tree?

I hope that the error messages produced by the analyzer will prove
self-explanatory.  The analyzer returns the number of errors it
detected to the shell (i.e. like a compiler).

The analyzer has to believe PICO about the bounds of subproblems and
the values of the incumbent.  The best it can do is make sure that
bounds trend the right way (for example, for a minimization problem,
that children have bounds greater than or equal to their parents).
Thus it is useful mainly for debugging PICO's parallel work
distribution mechanisms.

If the analysis is successful, you should see output like:

	5 processors.
	Solution value is 157.
	21 subproblems.
	No errors.

It is not necessarily a problem if the number of processors output is
less than the number that were actually used.  The number of
processors output by logAnalyze is actually the rank+1 of the
highest-numbered processor that created a subproblem.  When the ratio
of subproblem to processors is very low (as in the above example), it
is entirely possible that some processors never get an opportunity to
create a subproblem, even though they might get an opportunity to do
some bounding.

By default, the log analyzer expects each split operation to yield at
least 2 subproblems when split.  In some cases, for instance when
separation can be used to improve bounds, 0 may be a valid number of
children.  To change the minimum number of children, add "-minChildren
n" to the log analyzer command line, where n is any nonnegative
integer.  The "minChildren" parameter is defined only for the log
analyzer, not for the rest of PICO.


